    <div class="qanda">
        <h2>What is the purpose of this study?</h2>
       We are trying to understand how people learn the characteristic pattern of sounds in a language, and to see whether they do it using the same learning processes that are used for learning non-linguistic patterns. 
    </div>

   <div class="qanda">
	<h2>What will happen if you take part in the study?</h2>
You will study words in a made-up foreign language (by listening to them, reading them, and/or
pronouncing them into a microphone), then you will be tested on how well you can distinguish the
words of the made-up language from similar decoys. Finally, you will complete a post-experiment
questionnaire about what you heard in the experiment, and about your language (and musical
background), age, gender, and handedness.
   </div>

<div class="qanda">
	<h2>What are the possible benefits from being in this study?</h2>Research is designed to benefit society by gaining new knowledge. Your participation is important to
help us understand how people learn language, but you may not benefit personally from being in this
research study.
   </div>

<div class="qanda">
	<h2>What are the possible risks or discomforts involved from being in this study?</h2>
We do not think you will experience any discomfort or risk from the experiment. 
   </div>

